WEBVTT

00:01.627 --> 00:03.504
- OLIVER: Are you going out on a date?
- Date?

00:03.504 --> 00:05.839
No! Tobert has
a suspect he has a lead on.

00:05.839 --> 00:07.591
I'm meeting him for a stakeout,

00:07.591 --> 00:08.759
and the place has a dress code.

00:08.759 --> 00:12.221
Jonathan?
Howard's sweet boyfriend was your guy?

00:12.221 --> 00:14.181
Who else had more to gain
from him dying, you know?

00:14.181 --> 00:15.307
Who's he hugging hello?

00:15.307 --> 00:18.143
He's wearing a red coat and a cap.

00:18.143 --> 00:21.563
That was Ben's private doctor.
One of those, uh, celebrity concierge,

00:21.563 --> 00:23.315
anything-you-need
prescription-filler types.

00:23.315 --> 00:26.443
You're here!
Welcome to my slice of New York.

00:26.443 --> 00:29.655
Hey, you know who was a real fucking pig?

00:29.655 --> 00:30.906
Ben Glenroy.

00:30.906 --> 00:33.200
You didn't mean to propose to me?

00:33.200 --> 00:34.284
No, I didn't.

00:34.284 --> 00:35.619
♪

00:35.619 --> 00:37.496
Mabel, be my partner.

00:37.496 --> 00:38.914
I already have partners.

00:38.914 --> 00:41.542
The old guys?
No, they're busy putting together

00:41.542 --> 00:44.837
another bomb of a Broadway show,
which leaves you where?

00:44.837 --> 00:46.880
[kissing, moaning]

00:46.880 --> 00:50.217
Shall I draw us a bath?

00:54.012 --> 00:54.888
Oliver?

00:56.265 --> 00:57.724
I'm waiting...

01:00.477 --> 01:03.480
[dramatic thunder crack]

01:03.480 --> 01:06.483
♪ gentle music playing ♪

01:07.317 --> 01:08.527
[breeze blowing]

01:08.527 --> 01:11.905
HOWARD:
<i>Theaters are known for their ghosts.</i>

01:12.781 --> 01:14.324
<i>Take the Goosebury.</i>
[projector whirring]

01:14.324 --> 01:16.201
<i>In 1919,</i>

01:16.201 --> 01:20.080
<i>Gideon Goosebury was a rising star
on the Great White Way.</i>

01:20.080 --> 01:21.665
<i>But on opening night,</i>

01:21.665 --> 01:25.460
<i>playing the lovesick chimney sweep in</i>
Ashes to Ashes,

01:25.460 --> 01:28.881
<i>a 300-pound sandbag
came loose from the rafters</i>

01:28.881 --> 01:31.592
<i>and brained him in the middle
of his second-act monologue.</i>

01:32.301 --> 01:33.594
<i>Legend has it,</i>

01:33.594 --> 01:37.973
<i>if you don't sweep
Gideon's energy off the stage every night,</i>

01:37.973 --> 01:40.809
<i>he'll find a way to curse your show.</i>

01:40.809 --> 01:42.102
<i>There was the cholera outbreak</i>

01:42.102 --> 01:45.397
<i>that tore through
the company of</i> Hamlet <i>in 1949,</i>

01:45.397 --> 01:47.316
<i>John Gielgud's crippling shingles attack</i>

01:47.316 --> 01:50.694
<i>during</i> The Iceman Cometh <i>revival in '88,</i>

01:50.694 --> 01:53.989
<i>and now the death of Ben Glenroy.</i>

01:53.989 --> 01:55.032
[thunder rumbles]

01:55.032 --> 01:57.034
♪

01:57.993 --> 02:00.078
<i>When you make the stage
a part of your life,</i>

02:00.078 --> 02:03.457
<i>it can be hard to escape
your personal ghosts, too.</i>

02:03.457 --> 02:05.667
[thunder continues]

02:06.668 --> 02:08.337
<i>Your obsessions.</i>

02:08.337 --> 02:10.088
<i>Your failures.</i>

02:10.088 --> 02:13.091
<i>Just when you think you've broken free
from your old patterns,</i>

02:14.051 --> 02:15.469
<i>boom.</i>

02:15.469 --> 02:17.513
<i>They come back to haunt you.</i>

02:17.513 --> 02:19.932
CHARLES:
I know, President McKinley,

02:19.932 --> 02:22.100
Joy took everything.

02:22.100 --> 02:24.269
Except you and me.

02:24.269 --> 02:26.605
The guys with the attitude problems.

02:26.605 --> 02:29.441
[thunder cracks]

02:29.441 --> 02:30.651
But we'll be fine.

02:31.401 --> 02:33.987
We have each other.

02:33.987 --> 02:37.157
HOWARD: <i>But what do you do
when your future starts haunting you?</i>

02:37.157 --> 02:40.244
<i>The choices you'll never make.
The lives you'll never lead.</i>

02:40.244 --> 02:41.787
[banging on door]

02:41.787 --> 02:44.122
<i>What's more dangerous</i>

02:44.122 --> 02:46.208
<i>than someone whose dreams have died?</i>

02:46.208 --> 02:47.668
Howard! What's wrong?

02:47.668 --> 02:49.753
I have something I need to confess.

02:51.255 --> 02:53.257
I killed Ben Glenroy.

02:53.257 --> 02:54.675
[thunder cracks]

02:54.675 --> 02:57.678
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

02:57.678 --> 03:00.681
♪ vocalizing ♪

03:40.721 --> 03:43.515
[thunder rumbling]

03:43.515 --> 03:45.350
HOWARD:
<i>Legend has it,</i>

03:45.350 --> 03:46.935
three sweeps to the north,

03:46.935 --> 03:49.813
three sweeps to the south, you're safe.

03:49.813 --> 03:52.816
I did that every night during
<i>Death Rattle.</i>

03:52.816 --> 03:54.484
But on opening night,

03:54.484 --> 03:56.403
[sob] I didn't sweep

03:56.403 --> 03:58.405
[shudders] and Ben died!

03:58.405 --> 04:00.949
- [thunder rumbles]
- [sighs] Hold on.

04:00.949 --> 04:03.368
I thought you said
<i>you</i> killed Ben Glenroy.

04:03.368 --> 04:04.703
Yes.
CHARLES: Now, you're saying

04:04.703 --> 04:06.788
a ghost killed Ben Glenroy.

04:06.788 --> 04:08.832
Yes, Charles! It's perfectly simple!

04:08.832 --> 04:12.211
I was protecting our show
from a malevolent spirit

04:12.211 --> 04:14.087
with a nightly sweeping ritual.

04:14.087 --> 04:15.672
[sighs] But on opening night,

04:15.672 --> 04:18.926
I went to get the broom from KT's office

04:19.927 --> 04:21.595
and it was locked.

04:22.346 --> 04:25.432
Strange noises coming from within.

04:25.432 --> 04:28.852
I should have found her.
I should have gotten the key.

04:28.852 --> 04:32.648
But I try to never interact with KT
because of her casual cruelty.

04:32.648 --> 04:33.857
And her breath.

04:33.857 --> 04:36.985
So I didn't sweep, and five hours later,

04:37.486 --> 04:39.404
Ben was dead! [sobs]

04:39.404 --> 04:42.908
Howard, why haven't you
told anyone about this before?

04:42.908 --> 04:44.993
I guess I convinced myself
it was all in my head.

04:45.702 --> 04:47.704
But then, this morning,

04:49.206 --> 04:51.834
I saw him.
ALL: Who?

04:51.834 --> 04:54.419
Gideon.
[thunder cracks]

04:54.419 --> 04:57.005
I was at the theater.

04:57.005 --> 04:58.882
I was sweeping

04:58.882 --> 05:00.717
because we're moving back
into the theater tomorrow

05:00.717 --> 05:03.262
and I wanna make sure
it's completely ghost-free.

05:05.556 --> 05:07.474
And I heard a noise.

05:07.474 --> 05:09.768
[thunder rumbles]

05:12.062 --> 05:14.064
[eerie chirp]

05:14.064 --> 05:16.817
[soft buzzing]

05:16.817 --> 05:19.820
♪ eerie music playing ♪

05:19.820 --> 05:22.614
[buzzing, whirring]

05:24.449 --> 05:25.450
[whoosh]

05:26.618 --> 05:28.453
[echoing]
<i>Hello?</i>

05:28.453 --> 05:30.706
<i>Is someone there?</i>

05:30.706 --> 05:31.707
[whoosh]

05:32.666 --> 05:34.710
<i>I know Krav Maga!</i>

05:35.627 --> 05:37.171
[narrating]
<i>And there he was,</i>

05:37.171 --> 05:40.883
<i>in his signature cap and red coat.</i>

05:41.550 --> 05:42.801
<i>I said...</i>

05:42.801 --> 05:44.428
Gideon Goosebury!

05:45.846 --> 05:47.514
Is that you?

05:47.514 --> 05:48.807
[narrating]
<i>And he said...</i>

05:48.807 --> 05:50.767
FIGURE [echoing]:
<i>Sure...</i>

05:50.767 --> 05:54.730
[maniacal laugh]
[screaming]

05:55.564 --> 05:57.065
[thunder rumbles]

05:57.065 --> 06:00.152
Howard, I hate to break it to you,
but ghosts aren't real.

06:00.152 --> 06:01.612
Oh, of course, they are.

06:01.612 --> 06:03.238
Ho! Man in towel!

06:03.238 --> 06:05.032
Yes, Charles, I'm aware.

06:05.032 --> 06:06.033
[Oliver sighs]

06:06.033 --> 06:08.327
Spoiler alert.
MABEL: Nope,

06:08.327 --> 06:10.579
not the correct usage of that whatsoever.

06:10.579 --> 06:12.706
- Plot twist?
- Still no.

06:12.706 --> 06:14.750
You know, I shot
a ghost hunter doc once

06:14.750 --> 06:18.086
and we spent an entire night
aboard the haunted <i>Queen Mary.</i>

06:18.086 --> 06:20.797
Around 3:00 AM, alone in the dining room,

06:20.797 --> 06:23.467
I saw her with my own two eyes,
the Lady in White.

06:23.467 --> 06:26.512
Did you know that Queen Mary
was England's first queen regnant?

06:26.512 --> 06:29.139
A lot of people think it was
Matilda from the 12th century

06:29.139 --> 06:31.350
but she was never actually crowned.

06:31.934 --> 06:34.728
Charles, if the goal was to offer
a more interesting anecdote,

06:34.728 --> 06:36.230
we're headed in the wrong direction.

06:36.230 --> 06:37.397
Hello!

06:37.397 --> 06:40.859
Is anyone hearing what I'm saying?!

06:40.859 --> 06:43.862
There is a murderous ghost
loose in our theater right now

06:43.862 --> 06:45.781
and he's coming from one of us next!

06:45.781 --> 06:48.742
[thunder cracks]
Oh! God! I'm telling you--

06:48.742 --> 06:50.577
- [crying]
- Howard, breathe!

06:50.577 --> 06:52.913
Hey, just, uh, give us a moment. Hm?

06:52.913 --> 06:54.498
Hey, what's up with your tooth?

06:54.498 --> 06:56.416
Oh, it's a temporary. If I like it,

06:56.416 --> 06:59.294
the dentist says he'll do
the rest to match. What do you think?

06:59.294 --> 07:02.214
- Bright. Like a headlight.
- Oh. Ah.

07:02.673 --> 07:05.384
Okay. Obviously,
Howard didn't see an actual ghost

07:05.384 --> 07:07.386
but I still think it's worthwhile
us going over there.

07:07.386 --> 07:08.804
Oh, I totally agree.

07:08.804 --> 07:11.181
S-- [laughs] Sorry.
We're having a conversation here.

07:11.181 --> 07:13.350
Mabel, did you hear what he said
about the cap and the red coat?

07:13.350 --> 07:15.394
- I mean, it kinda sounds like...
- Ben's doctor?

07:15.394 --> 07:16.812
I had the same thought.
OLIVER: Jesus.

07:16.812 --> 07:20.482
Right, so he saw us last night,
and then realized he'd been made...

07:20.482 --> 07:23.527
So he goes straight to the theater
this morning to cover his tracks.

07:23.527 --> 07:26.238
Exactly. I mean, if he and Jonathan
are behind the poisoning,

07:26.238 --> 07:28.448
then they'd definitely wanna
make sure there's no evidence.

07:28.448 --> 07:30.826
That's good.
[clears throat loudly]

07:30.826 --> 07:33.620
Oh, sorry. Hi! We're still here.

07:33.620 --> 07:35.497
Yeah, the original three
who came into the dining room.

07:35.497 --> 07:36.623
Yeah, remember that?

07:36.623 --> 07:37.624
Yeah.

07:39.001 --> 07:40.794
You suspect Jonathan now?

07:40.794 --> 07:42.963
And you're investigating with this guy?

07:42.963 --> 07:46.466
Jonathan <i>was</i> Ben's understudy.
That's a pretty big motive.

07:46.466 --> 07:49.887
And I told you I was going on a stakeout
with Tobert last night.

07:49.887 --> 07:52.681
Oh yeah. Right. I forgot.

07:52.681 --> 07:54.850
I was probably preoccupied with Joy,

07:54.850 --> 07:57.811
who left me, by the way. Spoiler alert.

07:57.811 --> 08:00.439
Wait, Joy left you? When?

08:00.439 --> 08:02.691
- CHARLES: Yesterday.
- Are you okay, Charles?

08:02.691 --> 08:04.985
Oh, I'm fine. I'm fine.

08:04.985 --> 08:06.486
This is not my first rodeo.

08:06.486 --> 08:08.906
This old clown's been
bucked by Lady Love before

08:08.906 --> 08:10.782
and got back up to ride again.

08:10.782 --> 08:12.451
Yee-haw!

08:12.451 --> 08:14.077
- Very convincing.
- Well, the point is

08:14.077 --> 08:15.704
I'm completely fine,

08:15.704 --> 08:18.957
and Joy did not write "fucking pig."

08:18.957 --> 08:21.084
- [thunder rumbles]
- Well, someone did.

08:21.084 --> 08:22.878
Is it possible this ghost thing

08:22.878 --> 08:25.130
is Howard trying to cover for Jonathan?

08:25.130 --> 08:27.090
He sounded genuinely distraught.

08:27.090 --> 08:30.010
And we all know that Howard can't act
his way out of a damp paper bag.

08:30.427 --> 08:32.846
Here's a thought.
Why don't I go with Howard

08:32.846 --> 08:34.806
to the theater alone?

08:34.806 --> 08:35.891
I'll throw him a bone.

08:35.891 --> 08:38.143
We can look into his ghost thing,
you know?

08:39.603 --> 08:42.314
- What?
- Nothing, it's just surprising.

08:42.314 --> 08:44.775
You haven't exactly been
driving this investigation.

08:44.775 --> 08:47.277
In fact, you've been anti-investigation.

08:47.277 --> 08:50.781
Well, why don't I make it up to you
with a little solo mish?

08:51.740 --> 08:53.659
Mish is short f-for <i>mishegoss.</i>

08:53.659 --> 08:55.744
No way. I'm coming, too.

08:55.744 --> 08:57.829
- If you're going, so am I.
- Alright, I'm gonna tell Tobert.

08:57.829 --> 09:01.375
Wait! Mabel, a word?
You know, we're kind of a trio.

09:01.375 --> 09:02.918
And we're not hiring.

09:03.502 --> 09:05.128
Alright, fine.

09:05.128 --> 09:07.506
This'll be fun, the three of us together.

09:07.506 --> 09:09.007
I've missed this.
[Charles and Oliver laugh]

09:09.007 --> 09:11.844
Hey! Jack, Janet, and Chrissy,
can we speed this up, please?!

09:13.387 --> 09:15.222
It's a <i>Three's Company</i> reference!

09:15.222 --> 09:17.432
Those were the original
character names on the show

09:17.432 --> 09:19.768
before they changed Chrissy to Cindy!

09:19.768 --> 09:20.978
Why the fuck am I yelling?!

09:20.978 --> 09:22.938
Oh, oh, oh, oh, I know!
Because there is

09:22.938 --> 09:24.731
a murderous ghost on the loose!
[thunder cracks]

09:24.731 --> 09:26.733
[door clangs]
[thunder rumbling]

09:26.733 --> 09:30.237
[shivering, gasping]

09:30.237 --> 09:32.656
[Oliver groaning]

09:32.656 --> 09:34.658
[echoing door slam]

09:34.658 --> 09:37.578
- [quietly] It's dark in here.
- [loudly] Except for the ghost light.

09:37.578 --> 09:38.579
[shushing]

09:38.579 --> 09:40.914
Whoever Howard saw might still be here.
Keep it down.

09:40.914 --> 09:43.292
[quietly]
I'm sorry. I was saying the ghost light

09:43.292 --> 09:45.085
is an old theater tradition.

09:45.085 --> 09:47.171
It has to stay on at all times,

09:47.171 --> 09:48.797
and it never ever goes out.

09:48.797 --> 09:51.049
[light fizzles]
[Howard gasps]

09:51.049 --> 09:52.759
Nonbeliever says what?

09:52.759 --> 09:55.012
That <i>was</i> kinda strange.

09:55.012 --> 09:57.890
No, no, KT probably did it.
She must be here running cues.

09:58.265 --> 10:01.935
Why don't you all go see
if she's in the booth behind the balcony

10:01.935 --> 10:04.897
and I'll look around the dressing rooms?
Good? Good.

10:04.897 --> 10:07.399
No! We have to stick together.

10:07.399 --> 10:09.401
That's right.
First rule of every horror movie.

10:09.401 --> 10:11.361
Never get separated.
[Oliver grunts]

10:11.361 --> 10:14.031
All this commotion can't be good
for President McKinley.

10:14.031 --> 10:17.743
- The fish is named President McKinley?
- Why is he here with us again?

10:17.743 --> 10:20.787
Imagine you're in a fish tank
all day long, and you look out,

10:20.787 --> 10:22.748
and you see two people walking by.

10:22.748 --> 10:25.709
And then one day, you only see one.

10:25.709 --> 10:26.877
He could be traumatized.

10:26.877 --> 10:28.879
[echoing thud]
[Howard yelps, gasps]

10:29.796 --> 10:31.340
That's exactly how Gideon died.

10:31.340 --> 10:32.883
It is?

10:32.883 --> 10:35.093
Could Gideon be out for me now?

10:35.093 --> 10:37.095
Charles, do not make this all about you!

10:37.095 --> 10:39.139
[rope whips, sandbag thuds]
[all yelp]

10:39.139 --> 10:42.142
Okay, maybe it is about you.

10:42.142 --> 10:45.479
[rope creaking]

10:45.479 --> 10:48.857
♪ eerie crescendo ♪

10:51.985 --> 10:54.863
- [thunder rumbles]
- Oh God, oh God, oh God.

10:57.324 --> 10:58.784
Broom! I need that broom!

10:58.784 --> 11:01.537
Damn it, Howard, you made me
fuck up my highlighting.

11:03.038 --> 11:05.874
[shredder whirring]

11:05.874 --> 11:07.751
KT, we may have an issue.

11:07.751 --> 11:10.754
The issue is I was just nearly killed
by two falling sandbags.

11:10.754 --> 11:12.923
Ladies and gentlemen, stay calm.

11:12.923 --> 11:14.925
I'm gonna need everyone
to keep the stage clear

11:14.925 --> 11:16.844
while I safety check the flies.

11:16.844 --> 11:18.846
Now, who has small hands
who can help me test the ropes?

11:18.846 --> 11:21.932
Take Howard. He has hands
like an American Girl doll.

11:21.932 --> 11:24.226
- I do not.
- Howard, go with KT.

11:24.226 --> 11:25.769
Do <i>literally</i> whatever she says.

11:25.769 --> 11:26.770
[Howard groans]

11:30.440 --> 11:31.483
MABEL:
Hey.

11:32.526 --> 11:35.612
- Is this an attendance sheet?
- Yeah, it's a sign-in sheet.

11:35.612 --> 11:37.698
You sign in when you come in at half hour.

11:37.698 --> 11:39.408
Handwriting samples from the whole cast.

11:39.408 --> 11:41.285
We can use this to compare

11:41.285 --> 11:42.995
to the "fucking pig"
on Ben's mirror.

11:43.787 --> 11:46.039
Oh, I don't know.
I don't think that would be very helpful.

11:46.039 --> 11:48.500
It's exactly the kind of thing
that you would do.

11:48.500 --> 11:50.961
I basically pulled it from
the Oliver Putnam playbook.

11:50.961 --> 11:53.547
Well, that playbook
is mine to play with,

11:53.547 --> 11:55.299
so gimme that.

11:56.216 --> 11:58.594
Is he leaking?
His water seems low.

11:59.511 --> 12:01.889
I still don't understand
why you brought him.

12:02.681 --> 12:04.391
Oh. Well,

12:04.391 --> 12:06.894
this is a little embarrassing
to say, but...

12:07.644 --> 12:09.897
this fish is all I have right now.

12:09.897 --> 12:12.316
It's not like all of us
have hot new boyfriends.

12:12.316 --> 12:14.484
Tobert is not my boyfriend.

12:14.484 --> 12:16.403
Oh, so you do pronounce the final T.

12:16.403 --> 12:18.989
It's not like a French cheese. Tobere...

12:18.989 --> 12:22.451
[French accent] Uh, <i>garçon?
S'il vous plait,</i> I would like a <i>le Tobere.</i>

12:22.451 --> 12:24.453
- Oh, <i>oui, monsieur. Et votre--</i>
- Okay!

12:24.453 --> 12:27.206
- I'm just gonna cut you off at the cheese.
- Well...

12:27.789 --> 12:30.292
did you record
with him for <i>our</i> podcast?

12:30.292 --> 12:31.627
- No!
- Well,

12:31.627 --> 12:33.170
you showed him our Murder Board.

12:34.004 --> 12:36.548
And how about our red string?
Did you let his handsome fingers

12:36.548 --> 12:38.926
move our red string around?

12:38.926 --> 12:40.719
- Charles.
- Well, how can we trust you

12:40.719 --> 12:42.179
with confidential case information

12:42.179 --> 12:44.890
when we know you might share it
with a stranger at any moment?

12:44.890 --> 12:47.893
How can you trust me? Wha-- I...

12:47.893 --> 12:49.811
And he's not a stranger.

12:49.811 --> 12:52.481
We just have to be careful
who we get involved with.

12:52.481 --> 12:55.692
Yeah, and I think I have a better
track record with that than you.

12:56.235 --> 12:58.153
Tobert has done more for this case

12:58.153 --> 13:01.406
in the past two days
than you have the past two weeks.

13:01.990 --> 13:04.868
Okay, yeah. But I've been busy.

13:04.868 --> 13:06.870
Yeah, but I... [sighs]

13:08.038 --> 13:09.873
- Where the hell is Oliver?
- You know,

13:09.873 --> 13:11.792
President McKinley is definitely leaking.

13:11.792 --> 13:13.335
I need to find something to put him in.

13:13.335 --> 13:15.462
I think there's a props closet
down the hall.

13:15.462 --> 13:16.839
Yeah, you go ahead and do that,

13:16.839 --> 13:19.091
Oliver can do whatever
the hell he's doing,

13:19.091 --> 13:22.511
and I'll keep investigating,
alone, as usual!

13:22.511 --> 13:25.514
♪

13:27.683 --> 13:28.934
Okay...

13:31.520 --> 13:32.771
[sighs]

13:38.402 --> 13:40.863
I really don't see it.

13:41.905 --> 13:44.616
How many ways are there
to write an F anyway?

13:45.701 --> 13:46.952
[sighs]

13:47.703 --> 13:49.204
Son of a bitch.

13:49.204 --> 13:51.415
[eerie thudding]

13:51.415 --> 13:52.666
Guys?

13:53.542 --> 13:56.920
Th-There's something here
I think you should see.

13:57.921 --> 14:00.048
[thudding continues]

14:00.048 --> 14:01.300
Hello?

14:02.467 --> 14:03.510
Is someone there?

14:03.510 --> 14:04.678
[lights buzzing]

14:04.678 --> 14:07.306
I also know Krav Maga!

14:07.890 --> 14:08.891
Hello?

14:08.891 --> 14:10.434
♪

14:10.434 --> 14:12.436
I'm coming up, so...

14:12.436 --> 14:13.854
[light buzzing]

14:13.854 --> 14:15.355
I'm here.

14:16.523 --> 14:18.025
So...

14:18.984 --> 14:21.028
[grunting]

14:28.368 --> 14:31.788
My God, this looks like
the Phantom of the Opera's
college dorm room.

14:33.415 --> 14:34.958
[distant thudding]

14:35.876 --> 14:37.586
♪ dramatic sting ♪

14:38.712 --> 14:40.714
You're right.
I never should have brought you here.

14:42.132 --> 14:43.133
[door opens]

14:44.760 --> 14:47.429
Hello. Get you a little water.

14:47.429 --> 14:49.848
No problem. Ooh.
[faucet squeaks]

14:51.767 --> 14:54.603
You're an indoor fish.
You belong in a tank.

14:55.729 --> 14:57.773
Water is water, right?

14:59.566 --> 15:03.111
Hey, who loves you?
Go ahead, stretch out. [laughs]

15:03.111 --> 15:04.905
I'll be back to get you when we're done.

15:04.905 --> 15:06.907
[knob rattling, door banging]

15:07.574 --> 15:09.201
[nervous laugh]
Hello.

15:09.201 --> 15:11.036
[banging door]
Really?

15:11.036 --> 15:12.496
♪

15:12.496 --> 15:15.082
Hello? Hello!
[doorknob rattling]

15:16.917 --> 15:18.043
No need to panic.

15:18.043 --> 15:19.837
My friends will notice I'm gone,

15:19.837 --> 15:21.338
and they'll come back to get me.

15:23.924 --> 15:26.927
[emphatically]
I said don't panic!

15:26.927 --> 15:28.220
♪

15:28.220 --> 15:29.680
Ah!
[muffled yell]

15:29.680 --> 15:31.348
Ow!

15:31.348 --> 15:33.684
Jesus Christ, you bit me.

15:33.684 --> 15:36.478
Yeah, well, that's just the tip
of the incisor, you fucking...

15:36.478 --> 15:38.397
[machinery humming]

15:38.397 --> 15:41.108
Jerry? Jerry Blau?

15:41.108 --> 15:43.902
Oliver. Oh, thank God,
a fellow director.

15:43.902 --> 15:46.113
You shouldn't sneak up
on people like that, Jerry!

15:46.113 --> 15:48.657
I'm not a young man!
You could've given me a heart attack!

15:48.657 --> 15:52.244
I'm sorry, Ollie. I thought you were
someone coming to kick me out.

15:52.244 --> 15:53.745
What are you doing here?

15:53.745 --> 15:56.331
Donna fired you off this show a year ago.

15:57.666 --> 15:58.792
Are you living in here?

15:58.792 --> 16:01.879
No. I mean, yes. I'm squatting.

16:01.879 --> 16:05.424
But there's a rich tradition
of that in the theater, right?

16:05.424 --> 16:06.967
Right.

16:06.967 --> 16:08.886
I did spend a complicated three months

16:08.886 --> 16:11.096
living in Maureen Stapleton's mud room.

16:11.096 --> 16:14.266
But this is a different situation!
You shouldn't be here, Jerry.

16:14.266 --> 16:16.810
Just wait. I can explain.

16:16.810 --> 16:18.270
Have a seat.

16:20.022 --> 16:22.858
Can I interest you in a snack?

16:22.858 --> 16:24.443
No, I'm good. Thanks.

16:24.443 --> 16:27.362
It's so nice having company.

16:27.362 --> 16:29.865
[fizzling, snapping]
Oh!

16:30.616 --> 16:31.992
[light buzzing]

16:31.992 --> 16:34.494
Charles? Oliver?

16:34.494 --> 16:36.079
♪

16:36.079 --> 16:38.582
[eerie thudding]
[footsteps approach]

16:41.710 --> 16:43.754
♪ music swells ♪

16:44.171 --> 16:45.464
- Tobert?
- Wow. Look,

16:45.464 --> 16:48.050
I know that you wanted
to be with your guys, okay?

16:48.050 --> 16:50.802
But I decided to tail Jonathan
and he led me right here to the theater.

16:50.802 --> 16:52.095
[door opens]
Shh.

16:52.095 --> 16:53.597
[door shuts]
That's him.

16:53.597 --> 16:54.890
Alright, come on. Let's go.

16:55.599 --> 16:57.476
[clears throat] Maybe unhand me?

16:57.476 --> 16:59.228
- Oh! Yeah, sorry.
- Thanks.

16:59.895 --> 17:01.688
Hey, I'm glad you came.

17:01.688 --> 17:03.482
[light buzzing]

17:03.482 --> 17:05.317
[cables clanking]

17:05.317 --> 17:08.362
You don't like me, do you?
KT: You're irrelevant to the show.

17:08.362 --> 17:10.531
Therefore, you're irrelevant to me.

17:10.531 --> 17:12.991
Irrelevant?
I have been protecting this show

17:12.991 --> 17:15.410
from negative spirits since day one.

17:15.410 --> 17:17.579
And if you hadn't locked
your office on opening night,

17:17.579 --> 17:21.083
I wouldn't have missed a day
and Ben Glenroy might still be alive.

17:21.083 --> 17:23.418
[sighs] First of all,
my office door is never locked.

17:23.418 --> 17:25.003
It was locked on opening night.

17:25.003 --> 17:28.423
Not by me it wasn't.
And what negative spirits?

17:29.174 --> 17:31.301
Not Gideon.
[rattling]

17:31.301 --> 17:32.886
[whispers]
<i>You know about Gideon?</i>

17:33.887 --> 17:37.391
Fuck it, Howard,
I've done 43 shows in this building!

17:37.391 --> 17:39.142
Of course, I know about Gideon!

17:39.142 --> 17:40.644
Shh!

17:43.105 --> 17:45.357
But do you know
how dangerous he can be?

17:45.357 --> 17:48.026
I do. That's why I was sweeping.

17:48.026 --> 17:49.319
[chuckles]

17:49.319 --> 17:52.197
Fuckin' amateur hour.
Sweeping does nothing.

17:52.197 --> 17:54.283
- It doesn't?
- Mm-mmm.

17:57.077 --> 17:59.079
This is the closest I've ever
come to my dream job

17:59.079 --> 18:00.497
and I fucked it up.

18:00.497 --> 18:03.125
Your dream job was to be an assistant?

18:03.125 --> 18:06.128
No, an actor. I always wanted to act.

18:07.254 --> 18:08.255
But then, in junior high,

18:08.255 --> 18:10.716
I got cast as John Proctor
in <i>The Crucible.</i>

18:10.716 --> 18:11.717
KT:
Mm.

18:12.885 --> 18:15.387
[spotlight clicks]
It was thrilling at first.

18:16.638 --> 18:18.932
Feeling the spotlight warm my face

18:18.932 --> 18:21.935
the first time I delivered
my big monologue.

18:22.853 --> 18:25.439
[spotlight clicks, powers down]

18:25.939 --> 18:27.524
But after the show,
my mother told me

18:27.524 --> 18:30.527
my stage voice was matronly and shrill.

18:30.527 --> 18:34.031
She said she never wanted to hear me
use that voice again in public.

18:35.908 --> 18:39.411
So I quit before I even began.

18:40.996 --> 18:42.497
Damn.

18:43.040 --> 18:44.458
[inhales]

18:44.458 --> 18:47.461
I always wanted to be a director. [laughs]

18:48.879 --> 18:50.506
But that ship has sailed.

18:50.506 --> 18:52.424
Don't say that.

18:52.424 --> 18:54.134
You're not Gideon.

18:54.134 --> 18:56.553
You're not dead. Yet.

18:57.971 --> 18:59.806
[deep sigh]

18:59.806 --> 19:02.184
You don't sweep Gideon away.

19:02.184 --> 19:04.728
You have to include him. Come on.

19:09.900 --> 19:13.403
How long have I been abandoned?
One hour? Five hours?

19:13.403 --> 19:15.656
Nice to know I'm missed, huh?

19:15.656 --> 19:17.908
[sighs] You know what?

19:18.909 --> 19:20.953
Maybe you're right.

19:20.953 --> 19:23.539
If you piss off everyone in your tank,

19:23.539 --> 19:26.750
how can you blame <i>them</i>
when you end up alone? [scoffs]

19:26.750 --> 19:30.546
Wh-Why did I have to make fun
of that guy's name? "Tobert."

19:30.546 --> 19:32.548
It's a perfectly good name!

19:33.549 --> 19:35.300
But we're gonna get through this,
you and me.

19:35.676 --> 19:37.553
You don't mind if I relieve myself, do ya?

19:37.553 --> 19:39.471
[groans] I had two cups of coffee,

19:39.471 --> 19:42.015
and who knows how long
we're gonna be in here.

19:42.015 --> 19:45.978
[urinating]
[heavy breathing]

19:45.978 --> 19:48.814
- [sizzling]
- After Donna fired me,

19:48.814 --> 19:51.149
Marshall and I had a dispute

19:51.149 --> 19:54.403
about my ability
to continue paying our mortgage

19:54.403 --> 19:57.865
and I was asked to vacate the premises.

19:57.865 --> 20:00.367
Luckily, this place is free,

20:00.367 --> 20:03.662
as long as I don't get caught. Shh...

20:03.662 --> 20:05.789
So, you're the ghost?

20:05.789 --> 20:09.751
Your manservant
spotted me this morning.

20:09.751 --> 20:13.714
I heard him ranting
about Gideon Goosebury,

20:13.714 --> 20:16.383
and I thought if
I could pretend to be him,

20:16.383 --> 20:19.178
offer a few frights, drop a few sandbags,

20:19.178 --> 20:21.054
it might scare you all off.

20:21.054 --> 20:23.432
Long shot, I know, but...

20:23.432 --> 20:26.810
is there also any chance
that you killed Ben Glenroy?

20:26.810 --> 20:29.354
Really, Oliver? I'm offended.

20:29.354 --> 20:32.733
I may have suffered
a minor career setback

20:32.733 --> 20:35.652
but I'm not a monster!

20:35.652 --> 20:38.739
- [shoe thuds]
- Ah! Oh my-- Is that a rat?!

20:41.033 --> 20:42.701
You came on a good night.

20:42.701 --> 20:45.204
I doubt I'll have
a good night ever again.

20:45.913 --> 20:47.206
[sighs]

20:49.374 --> 20:51.001
You okay, Ollie?

20:51.001 --> 20:54.630
♪

20:54.630 --> 20:57.049
You know the first rule of theater?

20:57.049 --> 20:59.551
Don't feed Hugh Jackman after midnight.

20:59.551 --> 21:01.803
- The other one.
- Oh!

21:01.803 --> 21:04.556
You fell in love with one of your actors.

21:04.556 --> 21:05.682
Yes.

21:06.517 --> 21:08.602
- Lady with the braids?
- Mm-hmm.

21:09.728 --> 21:12.898
Now you're worried
because of her violent temper.

21:14.149 --> 21:16.818
What? Wh-What violent temper?

21:16.818 --> 21:19.321
Well, you know what happened
backstage on opening night?

21:20.697 --> 21:22.908
Oh! You don't know.

21:22.908 --> 21:27.037
Well [laughs] luckily,
you're not the only director here.

21:28.664 --> 21:31.208
[sighs] <i>Voilà.</i> Puppets.

21:31.208 --> 21:32.501
Oh good lord.

21:32.501 --> 21:36.129
See? I keep busy. [laughs]

21:36.129 --> 21:38.173
[urinating]
CHARLES: So then, I say to the guy,

21:38.173 --> 21:41.885
"Look, if you're so tough, then you ride
the moped into the chimp enclosure."

21:41.885 --> 21:44.388
And he goes-- [laughs] he go...
[flushes toilet]

21:46.557 --> 21:49.476
[wheezing]
<i>Mr. President!</i>

21:52.020 --> 21:55.023
♪ suspenseful music playing ♪

21:59.736 --> 22:01.530
- TOBERT: Thank you.
- Uh-- Give those back.

22:01.530 --> 22:05.033
- What's this?
- Dr. Hiram Camareri.

22:05.033 --> 22:07.244
- Dr. C, I presume?
- I don't know what you're talking about.

22:07.244 --> 22:10.330
Come on, Jonathan. You know we just saw
you with Ben's doctor last night.

22:13.208 --> 22:15.210
Alright. Fine.

22:16.962 --> 22:19.506
I've been <i>really</i> anxious

22:19.506 --> 22:21.717
since taking over Ben's part.

22:21.717 --> 22:24.178
It's a lot of pressure being the lead.

22:24.178 --> 22:27.181
So I asked Dr. C for some help.
He could get Ben <i>anything</i> he wanted.

22:27.181 --> 22:31.018
So he gave me the "leading man cocktail."

22:31.018 --> 22:34.605
It's a mix of beta blockers,
Propecia, HGH,

22:34.605 --> 22:37.107
and just a dash of methamphetamine.

22:38.525 --> 22:40.444
All the same things Ben was taking.

22:40.444 --> 22:43.197
So you didn't wanna be the lead.

22:43.197 --> 22:44.448
No.

22:45.324 --> 22:47.576
And please don't tell Howard.

22:47.576 --> 22:49.620
He wouldn't understand.

22:49.620 --> 22:51.163
It's his dream,

22:51.163 --> 22:54.249
but he has <i>no</i> idea what it's like

22:54.249 --> 22:57.753
to carry the weight of
an <i>entire</i> show on your shoulders.

22:59.505 --> 23:02.090
♪ somber music playing ♪

23:06.011 --> 23:07.262
[Tobert sighs]

23:11.850 --> 23:15.354
[sobs] Everybody knows you don't
take a fish in the theater, you idiot!

23:16.438 --> 23:18.315
Oh jeez!

23:18.315 --> 23:19.816
[water bubbling]

23:19.816 --> 23:22.319
[light splashing]

23:26.448 --> 23:29.076
President McKinley! Oh!

23:29.076 --> 23:30.577
Ho! Ho! Ho!

23:30.577 --> 23:34.122
I saved you from your second
assassination attempt.

23:34.122 --> 23:36.792
This is the universe telling us
that no matter what kind of hardships,

23:36.792 --> 23:39.127
we-- Wait. Is that an intercom?

23:39.127 --> 23:41.129
Hello? This is Charles.
[clicks, whirs]

23:41.129 --> 23:43.757
This-- I'm in the-- Can you hear me?
I'm in the prop room!

23:43.757 --> 23:44.842
[hissing]

23:44.842 --> 23:46.093
Hey!

23:46.093 --> 23:49.096
♪

23:49.096 --> 23:50.597
[clicking]

23:54.351 --> 23:56.228
Ah! Ah! Ah--

23:56.228 --> 23:58.981
[coughing]

24:00.107 --> 24:01.149
[laughing]

24:01.149 --> 24:03.485
Hey, w-we got a smoke issue!

24:03.485 --> 24:04.444
[buzzing]

24:06.405 --> 24:10.367
Now, at half hour
on the night in question,

24:11.451 --> 24:14.955
I saw Braids Lady

24:14.955 --> 24:18.125
jawboning with Mr. Movie Star Man

24:18.125 --> 24:20.836
while they were rehearsing
their big fight scene

24:20.836 --> 24:23.172
on the steps of the lighthouse.

24:23.839 --> 24:25.632
Something set her off.

24:25.632 --> 24:28.010
Probably Movie Man
taking the stage-choking

24:28.010 --> 24:29.803
a scooch too far.

24:29.803 --> 24:33.056
He gets rough, so she gets in his face

24:33.056 --> 24:35.809
and calls him, and I quote,

24:35.809 --> 24:39.438
a "Cocksucking ding-dong."

24:39.438 --> 24:40.856
That doesn't sound like her.

24:40.856 --> 24:44.693
I'm up in the rafters.
I'm only getting every third word.

24:44.693 --> 24:48.030
It could have been "fucking pig."

24:48.572 --> 24:50.824
Anyway, now,

24:50.824 --> 24:52.993
the Albino Fella comes along.

24:52.993 --> 24:54.536
You mean Charles?

24:54.536 --> 24:57.247
The has-been with the hair, yeah.

24:57.247 --> 24:59.666
He comes right in
the middle of all of this

24:59.666 --> 25:01.710
and clocks Mr. Movie Star

25:01.710 --> 25:04.379
right in the kisser.

25:04.379 --> 25:05.547
Blammo!

25:05.547 --> 25:07.674
Charles punched Ben?

25:08.467 --> 25:10.844
You didn't know any of this?

25:10.844 --> 25:14.556
♪

25:14.556 --> 25:16.308
Are you sure this'll work?

25:16.308 --> 25:18.894
It's worked 42 times before.

25:18.894 --> 25:22.356
And this is the actual monologue
Gideon was giving the moment he died?

25:22.981 --> 25:25.734
Yep. Now, call him to the stage.

25:29.154 --> 25:30.239
Gideon, are you there?

25:30.239 --> 25:32.407
Oh, come on! Use your stage voice!

25:32.407 --> 25:34.910
[echoing]:
<i>Sing out, Louise!</i>

25:35.410 --> 25:36.411
[sighs]

25:37.329 --> 25:40.791
- [yelling] <i>Oh, Gideon.</i>
- [projecting] <i>Your stage voice!</i>

25:40.791 --> 25:42.668
[deep stage voice]
<i>Oh, Gideon!</i>

25:42.668 --> 25:46.421
<i>We come not to banish but to praise you!</i>

25:46.421 --> 25:49.007
<i>Join us so we may finish</i>

25:49.007 --> 25:52.302
<i>your great unfinished work!</i>

25:52.302 --> 25:54.805
- Don't forget to direct me. [clears throat]
- Oh. Okay.

25:55.597 --> 25:58.308
[Howard clears throat]

25:58.851 --> 26:01.937
<i>"Oh, Irene, how could a poor sweep like me</i>

26:01.937 --> 26:05.440
<i>ever hope to win the love of
a fine lady like yourself?"</i>

26:05.440 --> 26:07.818
- It's a strong start.
- Thanks.

26:08.735 --> 26:10.696
[recording beep]
CHARLES: If you are seeing this video,

26:10.696 --> 26:12.698
it means that I am dead.

26:12.698 --> 26:14.074
I perished alone

26:14.074 --> 26:17.077
with only a fish as my witness.

26:17.786 --> 26:19.746
Now, I know what you're thinking.
You're thinking, "Charles,

26:19.746 --> 26:21.665
why didn't you scream?" Well, I did!

26:21.665 --> 26:23.709
"Why didn't you call somebody
on your phone?"

26:23.709 --> 26:26.628
Because I'm in a closet with no bars!

26:26.628 --> 26:29.298
"Why didn't you use your jimmy keys?"

26:29.298 --> 26:30.924
Jimmy keys?

26:34.219 --> 26:36.471
Hello, baby.

26:36.889 --> 26:38.891
What do we really know?
[sizzling]

26:38.891 --> 26:40.726
Loretta hated Ben.

26:40.726 --> 26:42.352
She was violent towards Ben.

26:42.352 --> 26:44.605
She had a motive
and opportunity to kill Ben.

26:44.605 --> 26:47.900
But, does that make her
a murderer or just...

26:48.817 --> 26:49.943
quirky?

26:52.613 --> 26:54.823
God, I'm screwed, aren't I?

26:55.657 --> 26:59.244
Oliver, how far do you and I go back?

26:59.244 --> 27:01.747
All the way back
to our original hairlines.

27:01.747 --> 27:06.585
All the way back to the dawn
of off-off-off-Broadway.

27:06.585 --> 27:10.172
And back then,
you told me the key to directing.

27:10.172 --> 27:11.673
Yes, I remember.

27:12.549 --> 27:13.926
- Remind me.
- You said,

27:13.926 --> 27:17.012
"The only wrong choice is no choice.

27:17.012 --> 27:18.764
Indecision is death."

27:19.932 --> 27:23.101
I said that?
Jesus, it's so bleak.

27:23.101 --> 27:25.270
You are not a young man, Oliver.

27:25.270 --> 27:27.606
You said so yourself.

27:27.606 --> 27:30.901
It's time to shit or get off the bucket.

27:30.901 --> 27:33.529
Choose what matters to you

27:33.529 --> 27:37.491
and then do
whatever you have to do to get it.

27:38.242 --> 27:39.993
Or you'll end up like me.

27:39.993 --> 27:42.454
Neither behind the scene or on stage.

27:42.454 --> 27:44.706
More dead than alive.

27:44.706 --> 27:46.959
♪

27:46.959 --> 27:49.378
Thanks, Jer. I know what I have to do.

27:49.378 --> 27:52.047
Oliver, you won't tell
anyone I'm here, right?

27:52.047 --> 27:54.049
I won't tell. But...

27:54.842 --> 27:56.969
you should really go home to Marshall.

27:56.969 --> 27:58.762
And eat his food?

28:00.389 --> 28:02.391
[Oliver sighs, grunts]

28:03.392 --> 28:06.186
- [door shuts]
- So Ben was on all of those drugs.

28:06.186 --> 28:09.398
Well, when Jonathan said
the cocktail had a dash of meth,

28:09.398 --> 28:11.358
why didn't that show up in his autopsy?

28:11.358 --> 28:14.069
- [loud bang]
- Oh! Oh, thank God!

28:14.069 --> 28:15.362
[wheezes]

28:15.362 --> 28:16.864
MABEL:
Charles?!

28:17.531 --> 28:19.074
- Mother?
- Charles!

28:19.074 --> 28:21.368
Oh! Mabel! I was trapped.

28:21.368 --> 28:24.288
Years went by! Do I have a beard?
Is <i>SNL</i> still on?

28:24.663 --> 28:26.748
You were gone for 20 minutes.

28:26.748 --> 28:29.334
Oh, well, I-I'm parched and I'm weak.

28:29.334 --> 28:31.503
You know what, let me see
if I can find you some electrolytes.

28:31.503 --> 28:33.881
Thank you!
Finally, someone's thinking about me!

28:33.881 --> 28:36.049
Thank you, Tobert!

28:36.049 --> 28:38.719
Did you ask him to come down here?
Are we partnering with him now?

28:38.719 --> 28:41.471
[sighs] He came here on his own
to follow a lead,

28:41.471 --> 28:44.474
like investigators do
<i>in</i> an investigation.

28:44.474 --> 28:47.436
Oh, I'm sorry, but who left who
to die in a fog closet?

28:47.436 --> 28:48.729
Who left...

28:48.729 --> 28:52.065
I swear, you and Oliver
are working my last nerve today.

28:52.065 --> 28:54.735
Really? Where is Oliver?

28:55.485 --> 28:56.486
Hey!

28:56.486 --> 28:58.864
♪ intense music playing ♪

28:58.864 --> 29:01.658
<i>"When I think of you
giving your heart to another,</i>

29:01.658 --> 29:04.578
<i>I die a thousand deaths."</i>

29:04.578 --> 29:07.831
- Bigger!
- [bigger] <i>"A thousand deaths!"</i>

29:07.831 --> 29:09.625
Yes, it's working! Okay, pace it up!

29:09.625 --> 29:12.085
[rapidly] <i>"I'll never rest until we're
together as we were meant to be."</i>

29:12.085 --> 29:13.962
Yes! Feel him inside you!
[buzzing]

29:13.962 --> 29:16.673
[echoing]
<i>Gideon!</i>

29:16.673 --> 29:19.301
Gideon is with us! [laughs]

29:20.844 --> 29:22.971
Oliver, stop! What are you doing?!

29:22.971 --> 29:24.932
- I'm making a choice.
- That's evidence!

29:24.932 --> 29:28.602
This isn't a crime scene anymore, Mabel.
The police got their guy.

29:28.602 --> 29:29.895
It's a dressing room.

29:29.895 --> 29:32.564
And since we're coming in here tomorrow
for rehearsal, it needs to be cleaned.

29:32.564 --> 29:34.066
Oliver, you're crossing a line.

29:34.066 --> 29:35.817
Oh, <i>I'm</i> crossing a line?

29:36.568 --> 29:39.196
This from the guy who punched Ben Glenroy
on the night of the murder

29:39.196 --> 29:41.573
and conveniently forgot
to tell us about it.

29:41.573 --> 29:43.242
You what? You punched Ben?

29:43.242 --> 29:45.619
Because he attacked Loretta
and I told him to stay away from her.

29:45.619 --> 29:46.995
But the real question is,

29:46.995 --> 29:49.164
why is your production so out of control

29:49.164 --> 29:51.750
that your actors are beating
each other up on opening night?

29:51.750 --> 29:53.377
Oh, this is my fault, is it?

29:53.377 --> 29:56.380
Well, you're the director.
Someone has to be responsible for the fact

29:56.380 --> 29:57.840
that your show is a death trap.

29:57.840 --> 30:00.092
Today alone, I almost died three times.

30:01.927 --> 30:04.930
- What?
- Two sandbags and a killer fog.

30:04.930 --> 30:07.057
Well, I'm so, so sorry
for trying to breathe life

30:07.057 --> 30:09.768
into your dead career
by putting you on Broadway.

30:09.768 --> 30:12.437
My career was not dead.

30:12.437 --> 30:15.649
Did you know that <i>Brazzos</i>
wanted to do burrito-sodes?

30:17.359 --> 30:19.945
Thirty-second bonus episodes
available exclusively

30:19.945 --> 30:23.156
on the Chipotle app but I said no
because I wanted to do this

30:23.156 --> 30:25.534
which I realize now was a huge mistake!

30:25.534 --> 30:27.202
Oh, it was, huh? Well maybe,

30:27.202 --> 30:30.038
<i>I</i> should have hired someone
who could actually sing!

30:30.038 --> 30:33.250
Well, maybe you should have
because I quit.

30:33.250 --> 30:34.501
- Fine!
- Fine!

30:34.501 --> 30:35.544
MABEL:
Charles!

30:36.170 --> 30:38.755
Why didn't you tell me
what happened with Ben on opening night?

30:38.755 --> 30:41.967
Because she was his girlfriend
and I was trying to protect him

30:41.967 --> 30:44.136
[stammering] 'cause he's my buddy!

30:45.053 --> 30:46.680
Was.
MABEL: Wait,

30:46.680 --> 30:49.725
Loretta's a part of this, too?
What else is she keeping from us?

30:49.725 --> 30:53.145
I don't know
and, frankly, I don't care.

30:53.145 --> 30:55.230
Oliver, what the fuck are you doing?!

30:55.230 --> 30:57.941
You know, you are like
a dog with a bone, Mabel.

30:57.941 --> 31:00.944
They arrested someone
for Ben's murder, remember?

31:00.944 --> 31:04.239
And yet, you keep trying to
throw suspicion onto my cast.

31:04.239 --> 31:06.491
You know, I know you've never
had a grownup job before

31:06.491 --> 31:08.619
but guess what?
They matter.

31:09.828 --> 31:11.788
- Wow.
- Oliver.

31:11.788 --> 31:14.124
In a few weeks, Loretta goes on to star

31:14.124 --> 31:16.752
in <i>Death Rattle Dazzle,</i>
and I finally get

31:16.752 --> 31:18.629
what I've been working for my whole life.

31:18.629 --> 31:20.506
I won't let you jeopardize that!

31:21.381 --> 31:22.591
Cinda was right.

31:22.591 --> 31:24.343
- What does that mean?
- Cinda Canning?

31:24.343 --> 31:27.763
Cinda fucking Canning
asked me to partner with her

31:27.763 --> 31:30.599
and I said that I was
already part of a team.

31:30.599 --> 31:32.518
She said that I don't need you guys

31:32.518 --> 31:35.145
and I'm starting to see that she's right.

31:35.145 --> 31:39.316
All I do is put up
with your self-involved insanity!

31:39.316 --> 31:42.611
The musical, the White Room, the proposal,

31:42.611 --> 31:45.155
but a man is dead!

31:45.155 --> 31:48.075
A man who actually meant something to me!

31:48.075 --> 31:49.785
And I'm gonna figure out who did it

31:49.785 --> 31:53.205
whether the two of you
give a shit or not! I'm done!

31:53.205 --> 31:56.208
♪ melancholy music playing ♪

32:00.379 --> 32:01.380
[sighs]

32:03.340 --> 32:04.883
HOWARD:
<i>Sometimes,</i>

32:04.883 --> 32:07.386
<i>all you need to banish your ghosts...</i>

32:07.386 --> 32:09.096
[wind blowing]

32:09.096 --> 32:10.681
<i>is for someone to see you...</i>

32:10.681 --> 32:12.975
Bravo!

32:12.975 --> 32:15.435
[birds chirping]

32:17.437 --> 32:20.023
HOWARD:
<i>...and understand your dreams.</i>

32:29.575 --> 32:32.578
[aquarium bubbling]

32:35.998 --> 32:38.000
<i>It's only when you're alone...</i>

32:42.004 --> 32:44.006
<i>that the real haunting begins.</i>

32:50.512 --> 32:52.514
[sizzling]

32:53.849 --> 32:55.142
[curtains slide]

32:57.019 --> 33:00.022
♪
